Prudently use the plastic tea bag to make the tea !
A packet of plastic tea bags could emit billions , if not billions , of plastic particles , significantly higher than the amount of microplastics a person is estimated to consume in a year , but there is no evidence yet that such particles pose a threat to humans , a new Canadian study has found .
Immersing a plastic tea bag into a cup of almost boiling water ( 95 degrees Celsius ) releases an estimated 11.6 billion plastic particulates and 3.1 billion smaller nano-plastic particulates into the cup , researchers at Magill University in Canada reported .
This number is significantly higher than the number of microplastics a person is estimated to consume over an entire year .
According to an earlier study published in 2019 , the average person eats at least 50,000 plastic particles a year , while inhaling the same amount of microplastics .
The study , published in the Journal of Environmental Science and Technology , tested four different types of plastic commercial tea bags in Montreal shops and cafes by ripping them open , washing them , immersing them in almost boiling water for five minutes and analysing them with an electron microscope and spectrometer .
They found that a single tea bag released more than 11.6 billion plastic particles , &quot; several levels higher than the previous plastic load of other foods , &quot; according to the study .
Most of the bags are made from natural fibres , but many are still sealed with plastic , the report said .
Some branded tea bags have switched from paper to plastic , which the researchers tested .
Plastic particles are tiny pieces of plastic , which the researchers define as range in size between 100nm and 5mm , and are produced mainly by the decomposition of plastic waste .
Researchers found traces of plastic particles in air , soil , rivers and the deepest trenches around the world , as well as in tap water , bottled water , seafood and beer .
Researchers first detected plastic particles in human stool samples from several countries in different regions of the world in October 2018 .
To test the potential toxicity of the tea bag releasing plastic pellets , the Canadian research team placed water fleas into already contaminated water and found that the microplastics could affect the behavior of the water fleas and cause developmental deformities .
To date , there is no evidence that the ingestion of plastic particles poses a threat to humans , according to the World Health Organization .
However , more research is needed to fully understand how these plastics spread into the environment and how it affects humans , the WHO noted .
The researchers speculate that the reason these tea bags emit large amounts of plastic particles may be that the bags come in contact with boiling water and can break down or ooze toxic even when the &quot; edible grade &quot; plastic is heated to more than 40 degrees Celsius .
