Study : U.S. national healthy eating index increase modest but still challenging - UPI.com
The U.S. government &apos;s healthy eating index has increased moderately over the past 16 years , from 56 to 58 , according to a new study .
But with a perfect score out of 100 , this is no cause for celebration .
Americans still face significant dietary challenges .
Americans are still eating too many foods that could lead to heart disease , diabetes and obesity -- the most common diseases among the American people , said Dr. Zhang Fangfang , co-author of the study and a nutrition researcher at Tufts University in Massachusetts .
The study was published online April 24 in the Journal of the American Medical Association .
The study is based on the findings of a U.S. government health survey of 44,000 adults conducted from 1999 to 2016 .
&quot; Despite significant improvements , significant dietary challenges remain , &quot; the authors wrote .
The challenges include getting Americans to cut down on snacks , hot dogs , fat cows , butter and other saturated fats .
The study found that people &apos;s daily intake of these unhealthy fats in their diets increased from 11.5 percent to 12 percent , exceeding the recommended limit of 10 percent .
The biggest improvement in the American diet is the reduction in added sugar from 16 % to about 14 % , but it is still too high .
In the official daily diet , added sugar intake should be less than 10 % .
The reason for the decrease in sugar intake has been linked to a decrease in sweetened soda consumption , but Zhang stressed that sugars are often added to even not-so-sweet foods such as yoghurt and ketchup .
There was a small increase in U.S. adult intake of fruits , nuts , oats , and other whole-grain categories .
Still , 2016 data show that these foods still account for less than 5 % of daily diets .
Although a slight reduction in salt intake and reduced consumption of fruit juices has led to the intake of low-quality carbohydrates , Zhang says they still account for as much as 42 % of daily calories , many of which come from processed white bread and other refined grains .
The study was based on individual health surveys conducted every two years that asked adults to recall which foods they had eaten in the past 24 hours .
These health surveys have asked this question twice every few days since 2003 .
The government &apos;s Dietary Guidelines for Americans recommend that people adopt &quot; healthy eating patterns &quot; to reduce the risk of chronic diseases .
The guidelines state that people should eat more nutrient-dense foods such as vegetables , fruits , whole grains , low-fat dairy products , and foods that provide protein such as seafood , lean meat , poultry meat , eggs , and seeds .
The number of Americans with diabetes nearly doubled during the study period , to more than 7 % , and the rate of obesity has increased for many years – roughly 70 % of US adults are now overweight or obese .
In addition , heart disease remains the leading cause of death among U.S. nationals .
