&quot; The shaft is all in the granite , because there are many crevices in the granite , which can &apos;t stop water running from the top to the bottom , no matter how much depth and water pressure the well is . &quot;
China Railway Tunnel Authority Da Rui Railway Project Department Chief Engineer Si Jing Zhao told reporters that the shaft construction , a number of mud inrush , collapse and other dangerous conditions , construction invited experts to control the pulse of the site , more than 20 research and treatment projects .
&quot; When the inrush of water in the shaft is at its maximum , it reaches the bottom at a rate of more than 300 cubic metres per hour , at a depth of more than 700 m , at a pressure equivalent to the ocean floor at a depth of 700 m .
&quot; If water were not drained in time , it would flood 10 meters of wells in an hour , &quot; he said . &quot; We spend almost 85 percent of our time on water control and 15 percent of our time digging , &quot; he said .
In order to overcome the vertical silo No. 1 vertical joint development , mud inrush , water-rich granite and other geological problems , the use of &quot; probing , excavation , &quot; the combination of systematic water control measures , in order to reduce the construction risk .
