Economic and trade frictions affect the U.S. economic &quot; report card . &quot;
The US economic report card for the second quarter of this year showed gross domestic product growth slowed sharply from the previous quarter , hurt by a sharp fall in private sector investment and exports .
Analysts point to trade and economic friction and the resulting uncertainty as the main reasons for the decline in private sector investment and exports in the second quarter .
The final revision released by the US Commerce Department on July 26 showed that second quarter US GDP grew at a 2 % annual rate , on a par with earlier revisions , but significantly lower than the first quarter ’ s 3.1 % .
Consumption growth was the main factor supporting US economic growth in the second quarter , the data showed .
Personal-consumption spending , which accounts for about 70 % of the US economy , grew by 4.6 % in the quarter , boosting the economy by 3.03 percentage points .
In addition , government consumer spending and investment led economic growth by 0.82 percentage points .
In the second quarter , however , private-sector investment fell 6.3 % from the previous quarter , dragging down 1.16 percentage points of economic growth during the quarter ; exports fell 5.7 % from the previous quarter , and net exports dragged down 0.68 percentage points of economic growth during the quarter .
Private-sector investment fell sharply rather than maintain the momentum of growth last year as rising trade and economic friction and uncertainty hit business confidence , says Barry Knapp , managing partner at Ironside macroeconomic consulting firm .
Knapp believes that US corporate capital spending is expected to remain subdued over the next year under the influence of policy uncertainty .
Analysts believe that while consumption growth provided strong support for the US economy in the second quarter , there are increasing signs that trade and economic frictions and the resulting uncertainty have affected consumer confidence and adversely affected the outlook for US consumption .
The survey leader , Richard Curtin , a professor of economics at the University of Michigan , said that in a recent survey , 38 percent of consumers spontaneously talked about the negative effects of tariffs on the U.S. economy , the highest level in a year and a half .
On the future direction of the U. S. economy , analysts generally agree that the U. S. economy will continue to slow down .
But some experts say the performance of both the US industrial sector and financial markets would improve if trade and economic frictions were eased .
Kathleen Burch , a global economist at The Economist think tank , predicts that the U.S. economy will continue the gradual decline that it has had so far this year , growing at a slower rate than it did in the second quarter .
Mark Zandi , chief economist at Moody ’ s Analytics , predicts that , assuming that trade and economic friction do not continue to escalate , the US economy will grow by 2.3 % this year , and slow further to 1.6 % next year .
Ellen Hartzen , an investment manager at Putnam Investments , noted that the companies &apos; biggest concern today was trade disputes and the uncertainty they bring . If trade disputes had been resolved , uncertainties would have been greatly reduced and industries would have performed much better than they are now .
Matt Merry , equity strategist at Miller-Tabak Asset Management , said trade and economic frictions remain the &apos; top issue &apos; and a major cause of the large swings in U.S. capital markets this year , and whether they are properly resolved will be key in shaping the direction of U.S. capital markets for the rest of the year .
